# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animation-blending
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] The "morph target" is a deformed version of a shape.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] When applied to a human face, for example, the head is first modelled with a neutral expression and a "target deformation" is then created for each other expression.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] When the face is being animated, the animator can then smoothly morph (or "blend") between the base shape and one or several morph targets.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] Typical examples of morph targets used in facial animation are a smiling mouth, a closed eye, and a raised eyebrow.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] Early 3D videogames, such as Quake and Crash Bandicoot use per-vertex animation for all character animations.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] When used for facial animation, these morph targets are often referred to as "key poses".
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] The interpolations between key poses when an animation is being rendered, are typically small and simple transformations of movement, rotation, and scale performed by the 3D software.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] Not all morph target animation has to be done by actually editing vertex positions.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] It is also possible to take vertex positions found in skeletal animation and then use those rendered as morph target animation.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] An animation composed in one 3D application suite sometimes needs to be transferred to another, as for rendering.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] Because different 3D applications tend to implement bones and other special effects differently, the morph target technique is sometimes used to transfer animations between 3D applications to avoid export issues.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] There are advantages to using morph target animation over skeletal animation.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] The artist has more control over the movements because they can define the individual positions of the vertices within a keyframe, rather than being constrained by skeletons.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] This can be useful for animating cloth, skin, and facial expressions because it can be difficult to conform those things to the bones that are required for skeletal animation.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] Vertex animation is usually a lot more labor-intensive than skeletal animation because every vertex position must be manually manipulated and, for this reason, the number of pre-made target morphs is typically limited.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] Also, in methods of rendering where vertices move from position to position in-between frames, a distortion is created that does not happen when using skeletal animation.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] This is described by critics of the technique as looking "shaky".
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] On the other hand, this distortion may be part of the desired "look".
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] For large models, vertex animation requires significant memory and storage as the position of each modified vertex must be stored for each frame.
[src:animation-blending/blend-shape] In contrast, skeletal animation requires only the storage of bone transformations for each frame.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer animation is a digital successor to stop motion and traditional animation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Instead of a physical model or illustration, a digital equivalent is manipulated frame-by-frame.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Also, computer-generated animations allow a single graphic artist to produce such content without using actors, expensive set pieces, or props.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] To create the illusion of movement, an image is displayed on the computer monitor and repeatedly replaced by a new similar image but advanced slightly in time (usually at a rate of 24, 25, or 30 frames per second).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] This technique is identical to how the illusion of movement is achieved with television and motion pictures.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] To trick the visual system into seeing a smoothly moving object, the pictures should be drawn at around 12 frames per second (which, when animating on 24 frames per second, is called "animating on twos”) or faster (a frame is one complete image).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] At rates below 12 frames per second, most people can detect jerkiness associated with the drawing of new images that detracts from the illusion of realistic movement.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Conventional hand-drawn cartoon animation often uses 15 frames per second in order to save on the number of drawings needed, but this is usually accepted because of the stylized nature of cartoons.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] To produce more realistic imagery, computer animation demands higher frame rates.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Films seen in theaters in the United States run at 24 frames per second, which is sufficient to create the appearance of continuous movement.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer-generated animation is an umbrella term for three-dimensional (3D) animation, and 2D computer animation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] These also include subcategories like asset driven, hybrid, and digital drawn animation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Creators animate using code or software instead of pencil-to-paper drawings.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] There are many techniques and disciplines in computer generated animation, some of which are digital representations of traditional animation - such as key frame animation - and some of which are only possible with a computer - such fluid simulation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] 'CG' Animators can break physical laws by using mathematical algorithms to cheat mass, force and gravity, and more.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer-generated animation is a powerful tool which can improve the quality of animation by using the power of computing to unleash the animator's imagination.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] This is because computer-generated animation allows for things like onion skinning which allows 2D animators to see the flow of their work all at once, and interpolation which allows 3D animators to automate the process of inbetweening.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] For 3D computer animations, objects (models) are built on the computer monitor (modeled) and 3D figures are rigged with a virtual skeleton.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Then the limbs, eyes, mouth, clothes, etc. of the figure are moved by the animator on key frames.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Normally, the differences between key frames are drawn in a process known as tweening.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] However, in 3D computer animation, this is done automatically, and is called interpolation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Finally, the animation is rendered and composited.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Before becoming a final product, 3D computer animations only exist as a series of moving shapes and systems within 3D software, and must be rendered.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] This can happen as a separate process for animations developed for movies and short films, or it can be done in real-time when animated for videogames.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] After an animation is rendered, it can be composited into a final product.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] For 3D models, attributes can describe any characteristic of the object that can be animated.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] This includes transformation (movement from one point to another), scaling, rotation, and more complex attributes like blend shape progression (morphing from one shape to another).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Each attribute gets a channel on which keyframes can be set.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] These keyframes can be used in more complex ways such as animating in layers (combining multiple sets of key frame data), or keying control objects to deform or control other objects.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] For instance, a character's arms can have a skeleton applied, and the joints can have transformation and rotation keyframes set.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The movement of the arm joints will then cause the arm shape to deform.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] 3D animation software interpolates between keyframes by generating a spline between keys plotted on a graph which represents the animation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Additionally, these splines can follow Bézier curves to control how the spline curves relative to the keyframes.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Using interpolation allows 3D animators to dynamically change animations without having to redo all the in-between animation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] This also allows the creation of complex movements such as ellipses with only a few keyframes.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Lastly, interpolation allows the animator to change the framerate, timing, and even scale of the movements at any point in the animation process.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Another way to automate 3D animation is to use procedural tools such as 4D noise.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Noise is any algorithm that plots pseudo-random values within a dimensional space.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] 4D noise can be used to do things like move a swarm of bees around; the first three dimensions correspond to the position of the bees in space, and the fourth is used to change the bee's position over time.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Noise can also be used as a cheap replacement for simulation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] For example, smoke and clouds can be animated using noise.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Node-based animation is useful for animating organic and chaotic shapes.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] By using nodes, an animator can build up a complex set of animation rules that can be applied either to many objects at once, or one very complex object.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] A good example of this would be setting the movement of particles to match the beat of a song.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] There are many different disciplines of 3D animation, some of which include entirely separate artforms.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] For example, hair simulation for computer animated characters in and of itself is a career path which involves separate workflows, and different software and tools.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The combination of all or some 3D computer animation disciplines is commonly referred to within the animation industry as the 3D animation pipeline.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] 2D computer graphics are still used for stylistic, low bandwidth, and faster real-time renderings.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer animation is essentially a digital successor to stop motion techniques, but using 3D models, and traditional animation techniques using frame-by-frame animation of 2D illustrations.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] For 2D figure animations, separate objects (illustrations) and separate transparent layers are used with or without that virtual skeleton.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In 2D computer animation, moving objects are often referred to as "sprites." A sprite is an image that has a location associated with it.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The location of the sprite is changed slightly, between each displayed frame, to make the sprite appear to move.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer-assisted animation is usually classed as two-dimensional (2D) animation and is also known as digital ink and paint.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Drawings are either hand drawn (pencil to paper) or interactively drawn (on the computer) using different assisting appliances and are positioned into specific software packages.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Within the software package, the creator places drawings into different key frames which fundamentally create an outline of the most important movements.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The computer then fills in the "in-between frames", a process commonly known as tweening.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer-assisted animation employs new technologies to produce content faster than is possible with traditional animation, while still retaining the stylistic elements of traditionally drawn characters or objects.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] A Dinosaur's Story*, *Balto*, *Anastasia*, *Titan A.E.*, *The Prince of Egypt*, *The Road to El Dorado*, *Spirit: Stallion of the Cimarron* and *Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas*.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Early digital computer animation was developed at Bell Telephone Laboratories in the 1960s by Edward E.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Other digital animation was also practiced at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In 1967, a computer animation named "Hummingbird" was created by Charles Csuri and James Shaffer.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In 1968, a computer animation called "Kitty" was created with BESM-4 by Nikolai Konstantinov, depicting a cat moving around.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In 1971, a computer animation called "Metadata" was created, showing various shapes.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] An early step in the history of computer animation was the sequel to the 1973 film *Westworld,* a science-fiction film about a society in which robots live and work among humans.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The sequel, *Futureworld* (1976), used the 3D wire-frame imagery, which featured a computer-animated hand and face both created by University of Utah graduates Edwin Catmull and Fred Parke.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] This imagery originally appeared in their student film *A Computer Animated Hand*, which they completed in 1972.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Developments in CGI technologies are reported each year at SIGGRAPH, an annual conference on computer graphics and interactive techniques that is attended by thousands of computer professionals each year.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Developers of computer games and 3D video cards strive to achieve the same visual quality on personal computers in real-time as is possible for CGI films and animation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] With the rapid advancement of real-time rendering quality, artists began to use game engines to render non-interactive movies, which led to the art form Machinima.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] CGI short films have been produced as independent animation since 1976.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Early examples of feature films incorporating CGI animation include the live-action films *Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan* and *Tron* (both 1982), and the Japanese anime film *Golgo 13: The Professional* (1983).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] *VeggieTales* is the first American fully 3D computer-animated series sold directly (made in 1993); its success inspired other animation series, such as *ReBoot* (1994) and *Transformers: Beast Wars* (1996) to adopt a fully computer-generated style.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The first full-length computer-animated television series was *ReBoot*, which debuted in September 1994; the series followed the adventures of characters who lived inside a computer.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The first feature-length computer-animated film is *Toy Story* (1995), which was made by Disney and Pixar: following an adventure centered around anthropomorphic toys and their owners, this groundbreaking film was also the first of many fully computer-animated movies.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The popularity of computer animation (especially in the field of special effects) skyrocketed during the modern era of U.S. animation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Films like *Avatar* (2009) and *The Jungle Book* (2016) use CGI for the majority of the movie runtime, but still incorporate human actors into the mix.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer animation in this era has achieved photorealism, to the point that computer-animated films such as *The Lion King* (2019) are able to be marketed as if they were live-action.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In most 3D computer animation systems, an animator creates a simplified representation of a character's anatomy, which is analogous to a skeleton or stick figure.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] They are arranged into a default position known as a bind pose, or T-Pose.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The position of each segment of the skeletal model is defined by animation variables, or Avars for short.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In human and animal characters, many parts of the skeletal model correspond to the actual bones, but skeletal animation is also used to animate other things, with facial features (though other methods for facial animation exist).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The character Woody in *Toy Story*, for example, uses 712 Avars (212 in the face alone).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The computer does not usually render the skeletal model directly (it is invisible), but it does use the skeletal model to compute the exact position and orientation of that certain character, which is eventually rendered into an image.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Thus by changing the values of Avars over time, the animator creates motion by making the character move from frame to frame.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] There are several methods for generating the Avar values to obtain realistic motion.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Traditionally, animators manipulate the Avars directly.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Rather than set Avars for every frame, they usually set Avars at strategic points (frames) in time and let the computer interpolate or tween between them in a process called *keyframing*.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Keyframing puts control in the hands of the animator and has roots in hand-drawn traditional animation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In contrast, a newer method called *motion capture* makes use of live action footage.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] When computer animation is driven by motion capture, a real performer acts out the scene as if they were the character to be animated.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Their motion is recorded to a computer using video cameras and markers and that performance is then applied to the animated character.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Each method has its advantages and as of 2007, games and films are using either or both of these methods in productions.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Keyframe animation can produce motions that would be difficult or impossible to act out, while motion capture can reproduce the subtleties of a particular actor.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] For example, in the 2006 film *Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest*, Bill Nighy provided the performance for the character Davy Jones.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Even though Nighy does not appear in the movie himself, the movie benefited from his performance by recording the nuances of his body language, posture, facial expressions, etc.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Thus motion capture is appropriate in situations where believable, realistic behavior and action is required, but the types of characters required exceed what can be done throughout the conventional costuming.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] 3D computer animation combines 3D models of objects and programmed or hand "keyframed" movement.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] These models are constructed out of geometrical vertices, faces, and edges in a 3D coordinate system.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Objects are sculpted much like real clay or plaster, working from general forms to specific details with various sculpting tools.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Unless a 3D model is intended to be a solid color, it must be painted with "textures" for realism.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] A bone/joint animation system is set up to deform the CGI model (e.g., to make a humanoid model walk).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In a process known as *rigging*, the virtual marionette is given various controllers and handles for controlling movement.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Animation data can be created using motion capture, or keyframing by a human animator, or a combination of the two.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] 3D models rigged for animation may contain thousands of control points — for example, "Woody" from *Toy Story* uses 700 specialized animation controllers.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Rhythm and Hues Studios labored for two years to create Aslan in the movie *The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe*, which had about 1,851 controllers (742 in the face alone).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In the 2004 film *The Day After Tomorrow*, designers had to design forces of extreme weather with the help of video references and accurate meteorological facts.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] For the 2005 remake of *King Kong*, actor Andy Serkis was used to help designers pinpoint the gorilla's prime location in the shots and used his expressions to model "human" characteristics onto the creature.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Serkis had earlier provided the voice and performance for Gollum in Peter Jackson's *The Lord of the Rings* trilogy.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer animation can be created with a computer and an animation software.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Some impressive animation can be achieved even with basic programs; however, the rendering can require much time on an ordinary home computer.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Professional animators of movies, television and video games could make photorealistic animation with high detail.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] This level of quality for movie animation would take hundreds of years to create on a home computer.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Instead, many powerful workstation computers are used; Silicon Graphics said in 1989 that the animation industry's needs typically caused graphical innovations in workstations.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Graphics workstation computers use two to four processors, and they are a lot more powerful than an actual home computer and are specialized for rendering.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Many workstations (known as a *"render farm"*) are networked together to effectively act as a giant computer, resulting in a computer-animated movie that can be completed in about one to five years (however, this process is not composed solely of rendering).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] A workstation typically costs $2,000 to $16,000 with the more expensive stations being able to render much faster due to the more technologically advanced hardware that they contain.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Professionals also use digital movie cameras, motion/performance capture, bluescreens, film editing software, props, and other tools used for movie animation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Programs like Blender allow for people who can not afford expensive animation and rendering software to be able to work in a similar manner to those who use the commercial grade equipment.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The realistic modeling of human facial features is both one of the most challenging and sought after elements in computer-generated imagery.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer facial animation is a highly complex field where models typically include a very large number of animation variables.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Historically speaking, the first SIGGRAPH tutorials on *State of the art in Facial Animation* in 1989 and 1990 proved to be a turning point in the field by bringing together and consolidating multiple research elements and sparked interest among a number of researchers.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The Facial Action Coding System (with 46 "action units", "lip bite" or "squint"), which had been developed in 1976, became a popular basis for many systems.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] As early as 2001, MPEG-4 included 68 Face Animation Parameters (FAPs) for lips, jaws, etc., and the field has made significant progress since then and the use of facial microexpression has increased.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In some cases, an affective space, the PAD emotional state model, can be used to assign specific emotions to the faces of avatars.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] In this approach, the PAD model is used as a high level emotional space and the lower level space is the MPEG-4 Facial Animation Parameters (FAP).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] A mid-level Partial Expression Parameters (PEP) space is then used to in a two-level structure – the PAD-PEP mapping and the PEP-FAP translation model.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Realism in computer animation can mean making each frame look photorealistic, in the sense that the scene is rendered to resemble a photograph or make the characters' animation believable and lifelike.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer animation can also be realistic with or without the photorealistic rendering.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] One trend in computer animation has been the effort to create human characters that look and move with the highest degree of realism.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] A possible outcome when attempting to make pleasing, realistic human characters is the uncanny valley, the concept where the human audience (up to a point) tends to have an increasingly negative, emotional response as a human replica looks and acts more and more human.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Films that have attempted photorealistic human characters, such as *The Polar Express*, *Beowulf*, and *A Christmas Carol* have been criticized as "disconcerting" and "creepy".
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The goal of computer animation is not always to emulate live action as closely as possible, so many animated films instead feature characters who are anthropomorphic animals, legendary creatures and characters, superheroes, or otherwise have non-realistic, cartoon-like proportions.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer animation can also be tailored to mimic or substitute for other kinds of animation, like traditional stop-motion animation (as shown in *Flushed Away* or *The Peanuts Movie*).
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Some of the long-standing basic principles of animation, like squash and stretch, call for movement that is not strictly realistic, and such principles still see widespread application in computer animation.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The popularity of websites that allow members to upload their own movies for others to view has created a growing community of independent and amateur computer animators.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] With utilities and programs often included free with modern operating systems, many users can make their own animated movies and shorts.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Several free and open-source animation software applications exist as well.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The ease at which these animations can be distributed has attracted professional animation talent also.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Companies such as PowToon and Vyond attempt to bridge the gap by giving amateurs access to professional animations as clip art.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The oldest (most backward compatible) web-based animations are in the animated GIF format, which can be uploaded and seen on the web easily.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] However, the raster graphics format of GIF animations slows the download and frame rate, especially with larger screen sizes.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The growing demand for higher quality web-based animations was met by a vector graphics alternative that relied on the use of a plugin.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] For decades, Flash animations were a common format, until the web development community abandoned support for the Flash Player plugin.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Web browsers on mobile devices and mobile operating systems never fully supported the Flash plugin.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] By this time, internet bandwidth and download speeds increased, making raster graphic animations more convenient.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Some of the more complex vector graphic animations had a slower frame rate due to complex rendering compared to some of the raster graphic alternatives.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Many of the GIF and Flash animations were already converted to digital video formats, which were compatible with mobile devices and reduced file sizes via video compression technology.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] However, compatibility was still problematic as some of the video formats such as Apple's QuickTime and Microsoft Silverlight required plugins.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] YouTube was also relying on the Flash plugin to deliver digital video in the Flash Video format.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] The latest alternatives are HTML5 compatible animations.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Technologies such as JavaScript and CSS animations made sequencing the movement of images in HTML5 web pages more convenient.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] SVG animations offered a vector graphic alternative to the original Flash graphic format, SmartSketch.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] YouTube offers an HTML5 alternative for digital video.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] APNG (Animated PNG) offered a raster graphic alternative to animated GIF files that enables multi-level transparency not available in GIFs.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Computer animation uses different techniques to produce animations.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Most frequently, sophisticated mathematics is used to manipulate complex three-dimensional polygons, apply "textures", lighting and other effects to the polygons and finally rendering the complete image.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] A sophisticated graphical user interface may be used to create the animation and arrange its choreography.
[src:animation-blending/computer-animation] Another technique called constructive solid geometry defines objects by conducting Boolean operations on regular shapes, and has the advantage that animations may be accurately produced at any resolution.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Traditional inbetweening involves the use of a light table to draw a set of pencil and paper drawings.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] The process of inbetweening in traditional animation starts with a primary artist, who draws key frames to define movement.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] After the testing and approval of a rough animation, the scene is passed down to assistants, who perform clean-up and add necessary inbetweening.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] In large studios, assistants usually add breakdowns, which define the movement in more detail.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] The scene is then passed down to another assistant, the **inbetweener**, who completes the animation.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] In small animation teams, animators will often carry out the full inbetweening process themselves.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Dick Huemer developed this system in the 1920s, and it has become widely used due to its efficiency.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Art Davis is said to be the first Inbetweener.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Typically, the key animator does not make drawings for all 24 frames required for one second of film length.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] In large studios, a specialized inbetweener artist fills in the gaps between the key drawings.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Only very fast movements require 24 drawings per second, which is referred to as animating "on ones".
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Most movements can be done with 12 drawings per second—called animating "on twos", drawing one out of every two frames.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] When the number of in-betweens is too few, such as four drawings per second, an animation may begin to lose the illusion of the movement altogether.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Computer-generated animation is usually animated "on ones".
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Frame frequency often varies depending on animation style and is an artistic choice.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Animation "on twos" has been used for over 100 years; *Fantasmagorie* (1908), widely considered the first fully animated movie, was animated on twos.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Modern animation uses various techniques to adapt frame rates.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Slow movements may be animated on threes or fours.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Different components of a shot might be animated at different frame rates—for example, a character in a panning shot might be animated "on twos", while everything in the shot is shifted every frame ("on ones") to accomplish a panning effect.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Optical effects such as motion blur may be used to simulate the appearance of a higher frame rate.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] When animating in a digital context, the shortened term *tweening* is commonly used, and the resulting sequence of frames is called a *tween*.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Sophisticated animation software enables the animator to specify objects in an image and to define how they should move and change during the tweening process.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] The software may be used to manually render or adjust transitional frames by hand or may be used to automatically render transitional frames using interpolation of graphic parameters.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] Some of the earliest software that utilises automatic interpolation in the realm of digital animation includes Adobe Flash and Animo (developed by Cambridge Animation Systems) in the late 90s, and Tweenmaker, released around 2006.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] The free software program Synfig specializes in automated tweening.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] "Ease-in" and "ease-out" in digital animation typically refer to a mechanism for defining the physics of the transition between two animation states, i.e., the linearity of a tween.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] For example, an ease-in transition would start the animation out slowly, and then progressively get faster as the animation continues.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] An ease-out transition does the opposite, where the animation starts out quickly but then slows down.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] The use of computers for inbetweening was enhanced by Nestor Burtnyk and Marceli Wein at the National Research Council of Canada.
[src:animation-blending/inbetweening] They received a Technical Achievement Academy Award in 1997, for "pioneering work in the development of software techniques for computer-assisted keyframing for character animation".
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] In animation and filmmaking, a **key frame** (or **keyframe**) is a drawing or shot that defines the starting and ending points of a smooth transition.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] These are called *frames* because their position in time is measured in frames on a strip of film or on a digital video editing timeline.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] A sequence of key frames defines which movement the viewer will see, whereas the position of the key frames on the film, video, or animation defines the timing of the movement.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] Because only two or three key frames over the span of a second do not create the illusion of movement, the remaining frames are filled with "inbetweens".
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] In software packages that support animation, especially 3D graphics, there are many parameters that can be changed for any one object.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] One example of such an object is a light.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] In 3D graphics, lights function similarly to real-world lights.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] They cause illumination, cast shadows, and create specular highlights.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] Lights have many parameters, including light intensity, beam size, light color, and the texture cast by the light.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] Supposing that an animator wants the beam size to change smoothly from one value to another within a predefined period of time, that could be achieved by using key frames.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] At the start of the animation, a beam size value is set.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] Another value is set for the end of the animation.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] Thus, the software program automatically interpolates the two values, creating a smooth transition.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] In non-linear digital video editing, as well as in video compositing software, a key frame is a frame used to indicate the beginning or end of a change made to a parameter.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] For example, a key frame could be set to indicate the point at which audio will have faded up or down to a certain level.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] In video compression, a key frame, also known as an intra-frame, is a frame in which a complete image is stored in the data stream.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] In video compression, only changes that occur from one frame to the next are stored in the data stream, in order to greatly reduce the amount of information that must be stored.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] This technique capitalizes on the fact that most video sources (such as a typical movie) have only small changes in the image from one frame to the next.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] Whenever a drastic change to the image occurs, such as when switching from one camera shot to another or at a scene change, a key frame must be created.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] The entire image for the frame must be output when the visual difference between the two frames is so great that representing the new image incrementally from the previous frame would require more data than recreating the whole image.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] Because video compression only stores incremental changes between frames (except for key frames), it is not possible to fast-forward or rewind to any arbitrary spot in the video stream.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] That is because the data for a given frame only represents how that frame was different from the preceding one.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] For that reason, it is beneficial to include key frames at arbitrary intervals while encoding video.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] For example, a key frame may be output once for each 10 seconds of video, even though the video image does not change enough visually to warrant the automatic creation of the key frame.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] That would allow seeking within the video stream at a minimum of 10-second intervals.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] The downside is that the resulting video stream will be larger in disk size because many key frames are added when they are not necessary for the frame's visual representation.
[src:animation-blending/key-frame] This drawback, however, does not produce significant compression loss when the bitrate is already set at a high value for better quality (as in the DVD MPEG-2 format).
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] In mathematics, **linear interpolation** (sometimes **lerp**) is a method of curve fitting using linear polynomials to construct new data points within the range of a discrete set of known data points.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] If the two known points are given by the coordinates $(x_{0},y_{0})$ and $(x_{1},y_{1})$ , the **linear interpolant** is the straight line between these points.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] For a value x in the interval $(x_{0},x_{1})$ , the value y along the straight line is given from the equation of slopes ${\frac {y-y_{0}}{x-x_{0}}}={\frac {y_{1}-y_{0}}{x_{1}-x_{0}}},$ which can be derived geometrically from the figure on the right.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] It is a special case of polynomial interpolation with $n=1$ .
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Outside this interval, the formula is identical to linear extrapolation.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] This formula can also be understood as a weighted average.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] The weights are inversely related to the distance from the end points to the unknown point; the closer point has more influence than the farther point.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Linear interpolation on a set of data points (*x*0, *y*0), (*x*1, *y*1), ..., (*x*n, *y*n) is defined as piecewise linear, resulting from the concatenation of linear segment interpolants between each pair of data points.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] This results in a continuous curve, with a discontinuous derivative (in general), thus of differentiability class $C^{0}$ .
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Linear interpolation is often used to approximate a value of some function f using two known values of that function at other points.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] That is, the approximation between two points on a given function gets worse with the second derivative of the function that is approximated.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] This is intuitively correct as well: the "curvier" the function is, the worse the approximations made with simple linear interpolation become.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Linear interpolation has been used since antiquity for filling the gaps in tables.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Suppose that one has a table listing the population of some country in 1970, 1980, 1990 and 2000, and that one wanted to estimate the population in 1994.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Linear interpolation is an easy way to do this.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] It is believed that it was used in the Seleucid Empire (last three centuries BC) and by the Greek astronomer and mathematician Hipparchus (second century BC).
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] A description of linear interpolation can be found in the ancient Chinese mathematical text called *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art* (九章算術), dated from 200 BC to AD 100 and the *Almagest* (2nd century AD) by Ptolemy.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] The basic operation of linear interpolation between two values is commonly used in computer graphics.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] In that field's jargon it is sometimes called a **lerp** (from **l**inear int**erp**olation).
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] The term can be used as a verb or noun for the operation. e.g.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Lerp operations are built into the hardware of all modern computer graphics processors.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] They are often used as building blocks for more complex operations: for example, a bilinear interpolation can be accomplished in three lerps.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Because this operation is cheap, it's also a good way to implement accurate lookup tables with quick lookup for smooth functions without having too many table entries.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] If a *C*0 function is insufficient, for example if the process that has produced the data points is known to be smoother than *C*0, it is common to replace linear interpolation with spline interpolation or, in some cases, polynomial interpolation.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Linear interpolation as described here is for data points in one spatial dimension.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] For two spatial dimensions, the extension of linear interpolation is called bilinear interpolation, and in three dimensions, trilinear interpolation.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Notice, though, that these interpolants are no longer linear functions of the spatial coordinates, rather products of linear functions; this is illustrated by the clearly non-linear example of bilinear interpolation in the figure below.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Other extensions of linear interpolation can be applied to other kinds of mesh such as triangular and tetrahedral meshes, including Bézier surfaces.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] These may be defined as indeed higher-dimensional piecewise linear functions (see second figure below).
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Many libraries and shading languages have a "lerp" helper-function (in GLSL known instead as **mix**), returning an interpolation between two inputs `(v0, v1)` for a parameter `t` in the closed unit interval [0, 1].
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] Signatures between lerp functions are variously implemented in both the forms `(v0, v1, t)` and `(t, v0, v1)`.
[src:animation-blending/linear-interpolation] This lerp function is commonly used for alpha blending (the parameter "*t*" is the "alpha value"), and the formula may be extended to blend multiple components of a vector (such as spatial *x*, *y*, *z* axes or *r*, *g*, *b* colour components) in parallel.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] In geometry, **spherical linear interpolation**, commonly abbreviated **slerp**, is a function which interpolates between two points on a sphere, such that spherical distance from the starting point varies uniformly with the interpolation parameter.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] In computer graphics, it was popularized by Ken Shoemake for animating three-dimensional rotations, represented as quaternions on an abstract 3-sphere.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] When the interpolation parameter represents time, spherical linear interpolation results in a constant-speed motion along a great circle arc between the endpoints or a smooth and uniform variation between two three-dimensional rotations.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Slerp has a geometric formula independent of quaternions, and independent of the dimension of the space in which the arc is embedded.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] This formula, a symmetric weighted sum credited to Glenn Davis, is based on the fact that any point on the curve must be a linear combination of the ends.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Let *p*0 and *p*1 be the first and last points of the arc, and let *t* be the parameter, 0 ≤ *t* ≤ 1.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Compute Ω as the angle subtended by the arc, so that cos Ω = *p*0 ⋅ *p*1, the *n*-dimensional dot product of the unit vectors from the origin to the ends.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] A slerp path is, in fact, the spherical geometry equivalent of a path along a line segment in the plane; a great circle is a spherical geodesic.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] More familiar than the general slerp formula is the case when the end vectors are perpendicular, in which case the formula is *p*0cos *θ* + *p*1sin *θ*.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Letting *θ* = *t*π/2, and applying the trigonometric identity cos *θ* = sin(π/2 − *θ*), this becomes the slerp formula.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] The factor of 1/sin Ω in the general formula is a normalization, since a vector *p*1 at an angle of Ω to *p*0 projects onto the perpendicular ⊥*p*0 with a length of only sin Ω.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Some special cases of slerp admit more efficient calculation.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] When a circular arc is to be drawn into a raster image, the preferred method is some variation of Bresenham's circle algorithm.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Evaluation at the special parameter values 0 and 1 trivially yields *p*0 and *p*1, respectively; and bisection, evaluation at ⁠1/2⁠, simplifies to (*p*0 + *p*1)/2, normalized.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Another special case, common in animation, is evaluation with fixed ends and equal parametric steps.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] If *p**k*−1 and *p**k* are two consecutive values, and if *c* is twice their dot product (constant for all steps), then the next value, *p**k*+1, is the reflection *p**k*+1 = *cp**k* − *p**k*−1.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] When slerp is applied to unit quaternions, the quaternion path maps to a path through 3D rotations in a standard way.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] The effect is a rotation with uniform angular velocity around a fixed rotation axis.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] When the initial end point is the identity quaternion, slerp gives a segment of a one-parameter subgroup of both the Lie group of 3D rotations, SO(3), and its universal covering group of unit quaternions, *S*3.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Slerp gives a straightest and shortest path between its quaternion end points, and maps to a rotation through an angle of 2Ω.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] However, because the covering is double (*q* and −*q* map to the same rotation), the rotation path may turn either the "short way" (less than 180°) or the "long way" (more than 180°).
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Long paths can be prevented by negating one end if the dot product, cos Ω, is negative, thus ensuring that −90° ≤ Ω ≤ 90°.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Slerp also has expressions in terms of quaternion algebra, all using exponentiation.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Writing a unit quaternion *q* in versor form, cos Ω + **v** sin Ω, with **v** a unit 3-vector, and noting that the quaternion square **v**2 equals −1 (implying a quaternion version of Euler's formula), we have *e* **v**Ω = *q*, and *q**t* = cos *t*Ω + **v** sin *t*Ω.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] The identification of interest is *q* = *q*1*q*0−1, so that the real part of *q* is cos Ω, the same as the geometric dot product used above.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Here are four equivalent quaternion expressions for slerp.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] The derivative of slerp(*q*0, *q*1; *t*) with respect to *t*, assuming the ends are fixed, is log(*q*1*q*0−1) times the function value, where the quaternion natural logarithm in this case yields half the 3D angular velocity vector.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] The initial tangent vector is parallel transported to each tangent along the curve; thus the curve is, indeed, a geodesic.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] In the tangent space at any point on a quaternion slerp curve, the inverse of the exponential map transforms the curve into a line segment.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Slerp curves not extending through a point fail to transform into lines in that point's tangent space.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Quaternion slerps are commonly used to construct smooth animation curves by mimicking affine constructions like the de Casteljau algorithm for Bézier curves.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] Since the sphere is not an affine space, familiar properties of affine constructions may fail, though the constructed curves may otherwise be entirely satisfactory.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] For example, the de Casteljau algorithm may be used to split a curve in affine space; this does not work on a sphere.
[src:animation-blending/slerp] The two-valued slerp can be extended to interpolate among many unit quaternions, but the extension loses the fixed execution-time of the slerp algorithm.
